      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":12,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury – Plantar Fasciitis Recovery\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy (walk/run as needed)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"James, this first phase is all about rebuilding your foot's tolerance for load — nothing more, nothing less. Every run is capped at 20 minutes and stays fully within your physio's clearance: easy effort, walk breaks the moment any foot discomfort appears. We start at roughly your current weekly volume (8 km) and build no faster than 10% per week. Three days per week, with Saturday as your longest effort. Cross-training (swimming, cycling, upper body) is encouraged on off days to maintain aerobic base without foot stress. No speed work, no tempo, no exceptions in this phase. If pain flares, drop back to walking for that session — that is not failure, that is smart rehab running.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":13,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% moderate (no hard efforts)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"CrossTrain\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"If your physio clears continued progression and your foot has been pain-free through Phase 1, we begin extending your Saturday long run and adding a bit more volume to the week. Runs may now extend slightly beyond 20 minutes as your clearance evolves — but only with explicit physio sign-off. All running remains easy pace (5:25–6:12 /km). We still honor 3 days per week and include a deload week in week 3 of this phase. The goal here is building aerobic tissue tolerance, not fitness performance. Your pre-injury fitness will return faster than it took to build — that's the physiology working in your favor.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":19,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":24,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85% easy / 15% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":270,\"notes\":\"This phase is conditional: it begins only if your physio has cleared you for structured running beyond easy efforts, and only if the foot has been consistently pain-free for at least 2–3 weeks. A single short tempo segment (at your threshold pace of 4:30 /km) may be introduced mid-phase — but only once, only briefly, and only pain-free. Saturday long runs continue. Volume still builds at no more than 10% per week. If there is any doubt about foot status at the start of this phase, we simply extend Phase 2 — there is no rush, and protecting the tissue now pays off for the next 5 years of running.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Taper\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":16,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":16,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"A short consolidation week to let the body absorb the work from the previous 11 weeks. Volume drops back comfortably, all efforts are easy, and the focus shifts to how the foot and body feel heading into ongoing training. This is not a finish line — it is a platform. From here, with a healthy foot and a rebuilt base, you will be well-positioned to set a new 10K goal and chase it properly.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James has active plantar fasciitis with physiotherapist clearance for easy running only, capped at 20 minutes per session, with mandatory walk breaks if any foot pain arises. The plan is built entirely around that clearance first, and fitness second — because protecting the plantar fascia now is what makes future training possible. His pre-injury 10K of 44:00 tells us his aerobic engine is solid; the job right now is rebuilding tissue tolerance, not performance. All paces are drawn from his Daniels-derived easy zone (5:25–6:12 /km), and no speed work appears until Phase 3, which is itself conditional on physio clearance. Volume starts at 8 km per week — consistent with his recent training history — and progresses no faster than 10% per week, with deload weeks every 3–4 weeks to allow adaptation. Three days per week is strictly honored throughout, which also reduces cumulative foot load. Cross-training is woven in throughout to maintain cardiovascular fitness without adding foot stress. The 12-week structure gives the plantar fascia adequate time to heal and strengthen before any intensity returns. James's five years of running experience and his recovered runner's knee history both suggest he understands the patience this process requires — and that patience is exactly what will get him back to racing.\",\"warnings\":\"This plan operates within the constraints provided by James's physiotherapist as of the plan generation date. It is not a substitute for ongoing medical guidance. James must continue working with his physiotherapist throughout this plan and adjust or pause training based on their advice. If foot pain returns at any point — even mild discomfort — the session should be stopped and the physio consulted before the next run. No speed work, tempo, or interval training should begin without explicit physio clearance, regardless of where James is in the plan timeline. Plantar fasciitis is particularly sensitive to sudden load increases; the 10% weekly volume cap is non-negotiable. If James misses a week due to pain or setback, volume should resume from the previous week's level — not the missed week's target.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
